<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-781-938  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 781 938.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  August 14 1989 v3 n33 p7(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>GSA to unveil model for automating civilian-agency traffic.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Levine, Arnold S.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The General Services Administration's (GSA) Federal Supply Serviceis ready to publish a model for automating transportationoperations that can be used by civilian agencies.andP;  The model is arequirements analysis to determine what users actually need, notwhat they have.andP;  The model will lead to a system that bringstogether all of the functional requirements into an automatedsystem that different agencies can use.andP;  The system will betotally hardware-independent and use off-the-shelf packagesmodified to government needs.andP;  It may eventually interface withthe Defense Department's central automated freight rating androuting system.andP;  The civilian transportation model willincorporate prepayment audits and electronic data interchange(EDI).andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     TransportationAutomationComputer SystemsElectronic Data InterchangeUnited States. General Services AdministrationPrototype.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>